  "prompt": "Is \"sher\" (\u0936\u0947\u0930) a lion or a tiger?",
  "response": "The word \"sher\" (\u0936\u0947\u0930) in Hindi typically refers to a **lion**. However, in some contexts or regional dialects, it can also be used to describe a **tiger**. Generally, the distinction is made as follows:\n\n- **Lion**: \u0936\u0947\u0930 (sher)  \n- **Tiger**: \u092c\u093e\u0918 (bagh)\n\nBut in common usage, especially in poetry or colloquial language, \"sher\" is often used to denote both animals. To avoid confusion, the specific animal is usually clarified by context. For example, the Asiatic lion is called \"\u0938\u093f\u0902\u0939\" (sinh), while \"\u092c\u093e\u0918\" (bagh) is the standard term for a tiger.",
